:6287"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SAA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9782420992851257, "span": {"begin": 631, "end": 634}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3290"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HDL", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9857355952262878, "span": {"begin": 640, "end": 643}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9879606366157532, "span": {"begin": 691, "end": 696}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6287"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SAA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.993712842464447, "span": {"begin": 719, "end": 722}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1401"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "C-reactive protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9981335997581482, "span": {"begin": 727, "end": 745}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1401"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CRP", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954354763031006, "span": {"begin": 747, "end": 750}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9900484085083008, "span": {"begin": 789, "end": 795}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002318"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cardiovascular", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.8201503157615662, "span": {"begin": 920, "end": 934}}], "text": "The biological plausibility is high. During acute phase response, serum amyloid A (SAA), one of the major acute phase proteins, replaces apolipoprotein A-1 from high density lipoprotein (HDL). This replacement obstructs the reverse transport of cholesterol to the liver, allowing the accumulation of cholesterol in cells, denominated foam cells (Lindhorst, Young, Bagshaw, Hyland, &amp; Kisilevsky, 1997; McGillicuddy et al., 2009; Meek, Urieli-Shoval, &amp; Benditt, 1994). Foam cells are early markers of atherosclerotic lesions (Libby et al., 2019), and it has been shown that macrophages have a higher uptake of HDL containing SAA than HDL alone (Lindhorst et al., 1997).  The two major human acute phase response, SAA and C-reactive protein (CRP), have been shown to be correlated in humans (Baumann et al., 2018; Monse et al., 2018; Ridker, Hennekens, Buring, &amp; Rifai, 2000), and both are predictors of future cardiovascular event risks (Ridker et al., 2000).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:05:37 +0000 2026"}